North Florida women's basketball fought hard but fell short to Bellarmine, ending the game 80-69. The Ospreys came back from a 10-0 deficit to briefly take the lead but couldn't maintain their momentum in the final quarters. Freshman Jamisyn Stinson was the standout performer with 14 points, while Jasmynne Gibson contributed 10 points and seven rebounds. Despite the loss, the Ospreys showcased resilience against a tough opponent.
- North Florida outscored Bellarmine 20-10 off turnovers, forcing 12 turnovers.
- UNF scored 26 points in the paint and contributed 22 points from the bench.
While UNF showed significant improvement by narrowing a past deficit, their inability to maintain leads in the second half raises concerns about consistency under pressure. The Ospreys' offensive struggles may indicate deeper issues in their late-game performance.
State of Play- North Florida's record now stands at 4-18 with a winless ASUN record of 0-9.
- Despite the loss, the team demonstrated notable offensive capability, particularly from their freshman players.
The Ospreys are set to face Eastern Kentucky next on February 1, where they will need to focus on maintaining offensive momentum and tightening their defense to secure their first conference win.
Bottom LineNorth Florida must build on their impressive moments of resilience and transform them into a full 40-minute performance. Consistency is key if the team aims to overcome their current losing streak and build momentum moving forward.
